Relating this to other examples, Gödel’s theorems serve as a cautionary tale about the limits of purely formal, axiomatic approaches. Logical Positivism failed in part because it tried to create a strictly logical system for determining meaning and truth, but it couldn’t account for the complexities of human language and scientific theory. Hilbert’s Program aimed for a complete and consistent foundation for mathematics but was proven impossible due to these inherent limits. Marxist economic planning also tried to impose a logically derived, centralized system on a complex and dynamic reality, which didn’t work as intended in practice.

